    "output": "Yes, you can extract subtitle streams from an MKV file using stream copy without re-encoding. Stream copying copies the selected streams as-is, preserving the original quality and format. \n\nHereâ€™s how to do it:\n\n- Use the `-map` option to select subtitle streams (e.g., `-map 0:s` selects all subtitle streams from the input).\n- Use `-c:s copy` to stream copy only subtitle streams.\n- If you want to extract a specific subtitle stream, use `-map 0:s:<index>`.\n- Set the output container format to MKV or any container that supports subtitle tracks.\n\nExample assumes you want to extract all subtitle streams into a separate MKV file containing only subtitles.\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.mkv -map 0:s -c:s copy subtitles_only.mkv\n```\n\nIf you want to extract a single subtitle stream (e.g., the first subtitle stream):\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.mkv -map 0:s:0 -c:s copy subtitle_0.mkv\n```\n\nIf you want to extract subtitles into their original format as separate files (e.g., `.srt`, `.ass`), you would extract them individually like this (assuming the first subtitle stream is in SRT format):\n\n```bash\nffmpeg -i input.mkv -map 0:s:0 -c:s copy subtitle_0.srt\n```\n\nKeep in mind that this only works if the subtitles are in a text-based format supported by direct stream copy extraction. Some subtitle formats embedded in MKV (like PGS/subpicture) may need conversion for separate extraction.\n\nThis approach preserves the original subtitle stream without re-encoding or quality loss.",
